Monday's panic-buying following the announcement of a national state of disaster could have serious consequences. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The Consumer Goods Council is calling on South Africans to stop panic buying. The council's Patricia Pillay said it had a meeting with retailers and other stakeholders on the matter on Monday. She said an agreement was reached to ensure there is enough stock and that retailers do not increase prices on essential products. READ: Panic buying hits Singapore after virus alert raised "A commitment was made on a few matters, the most important was consumer awareness, in terms of ensuring that there is enough stock. That there is no need for them to be emptying out the shelves. There also is in terms of numbers of purchases on essential items that are in the stores, that there might be limitations," said Pillay. READ: What should you do if you think you have COVID-19? Following the announcement of a national state of disaster on Sunday, many consumers headed to supermarkets to bulk buy goods which led to stock shortages. Pillay urged consumers not to hoard goods. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.